In Object-Oriented Programming, delegation is an object's behavior or capability to be replaced by another object. In the case of your `List` class and its subclasses (like a stack), you can use delegate pattern in order to achieve this functionality without directly modifying these classes themselves. 

Here are some ways how we could implement it:

1) Using an interface or abstract base class for delegation, like so:
```java
interface Listable { void list(); } // Declaration of the Delegate Interface (Listable).  
class Stack implements Listable{ @Override public void list(){ /* implementation */ }} 
// Now any object that wants to behave as a `list` operation can do it by implementing this interface.   
```    
2) Using delegation in constructor: If you want the subclasses (like stack, queue etc.) of your List class also act like lists and have methods for adding elements or removing them then use delegate pattern with constructors to pass a reference/instance where list can be created from it using `super()`.
```java 
class Stack extends List { // Sub-Class that acts as an interface (List)  
    public void push(Object o){ super().addElement((T)o); }     /* implementation */}     
// Now any object of the sub class can call methods like `push` and it will delegate to list's method. 
```      
3) Using delegation in setter: If you want your List objects (sub-classes), also act as lists, then use a Settable interface or abstract base classes for setting elements at any time during the object’s lifetime instead of just calling methods like `addElement` and so on.  This way when an element is added to list it will be done by delegate pattern in setter method itself:
```java  
class Stack extends List { // Sub-Class that acts as a Settable interface (List)   
public void add(Object o){ super().addElement((T)o); } /* implementation */} 
// Now any object of the sub class can call `set` method and it will delegate to list's setter.  
```    
In all cases, you are not directly modifying your classes (List or Stack), but using delegation pattern in order for these objects/classes behave as a List-like behavior when needed by other components of the system like stack etc..  This is an effective way to decouple and make code more modular.

